content.thinking:
The hero h1 currently has:
```css
.hero h1 {
  font-size: clamp(48px, 8vw, 96px);
  font-weight: 900;
  letter-spacing: -3px;
  line-height: 1.0;
  margin-bottom: 24px;
}
```

The issue is that `clamp(48px, 8vw, 96px)` — on mobile (e.g., 375px wide), `8vw` = 30px which is less than 48px, so it clamps to **48px minimum**. 

That's why it looks too big on mobile. I should lower the minimum to something like `clamp(32px, 9vw, 96px)` instead, which would scale down to around 33px on mobile while still hitting 96px at larger viewports. For a hero title, 32-36px on mobile feels more balanced and tasteful.

The real issue is that the text breaks into three lines on mobile, so at 48px per line with standard line-height, I'm looking at nearly 150px of vertical space just for the text. I think `clamp(28px, 7vw, 96px)` or `clamp(30px, 8vw, 96px)` would be more sensible—the latter gives me 30px at 375px and scales up smoothly. I should also consider adjusting the letter-spacing on mobile since the aggressive negative spacing that looks sharp on desktop can feel cramped when the text is smaller.

Adjusting letter-spacing on smaller screens... I need the next thinking to rewrite. You've provided my current rewritten thinking and the guidelines, but I don't see the "next thinking" content that I should be rewriting.

Could you please share the next thinking chunk that needs to be rewritten?

